4_scRNAseq

Master Medical Biometry/Biostatistics, Introduction to Bioinformatics, Medizinische Fakultt Heidelberg

The purpose of these exercises is to introduce you to the post-processing of single cell RNA-seq data, in this case identification of gene markers.

Provide answers to questions that are marked with Q.

The Data

We will be using a dataset generated by 10X genomics, a leading company in providing single cell chemistry, hardware and software. The dataset includes 9k Brain Cells from cortex, hippocampus and subventricular zones of an E18 Mouse. Some statistics for this dataset can be found here, and in summary:

9,128 cells detected
Sequenced on Illumina Hiseq4000 with approximately 42,000 reads per cell

The data was processed using Cell Ranger, which:

  • generated the raw FastQ files
  • filtered and aligned the reads to the reference genome
  • counted barcodes and UMIs
  • generated feature barcode matrices

Download the filtered_gene_bc_matrices.zip folder unzip it.

Loading packages

There are many software packages for analyzing single cell RNA data; Monocle, Scanpy and Seurat among others. For todays practical we will use Seurat, one of the most common tools. Seurat takes a count matrix as input and uses several statistical methods to perform clustering and differential expression on the data.

Start R in your local computer.

Select your working directory (where you saved the filtered_gene_bc_matrices folder) by clicking:

Session -> Set Working Directory -> Choose directory

This is a copy/paste tutorial so we can focus on the interpretation of the results; however it is important to understand what each line is doing, so if you have any questions, just raise your hand!

Quality control and filtering

Here we will remove cells and genes that can create biases due to cell duplicates, cell lysis and cells with very few reads in total.

First, lets calculate the percentage of mitochondrial gene expression for every cell, this will give us an idea of the quality of the cells, for example, high proportions of mitochondrial genes indicate the loss of cytoplasmic RNA (e.g., perforated cells).

# Calculating mitochondrial content, in this case mitochondrial
# genes are annotated as "mt-Cytb"
neuron[["percent.mt"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(neuron, pattern = "^mt-") 
head(neuron[[]])
##                    orig.ident nCount_RNA nFeature_RNA percent.mt

## AAACCTGAGGTCATCT-1     neuron       2853         1367   2.979320
## AAACCTGCAAGAGTCG-1     neuron       7574         2594   4.264589

Normalization, data scaling and dimensional reduction

Now lets normalize the data so that we can compare the cells to each other and identify the most variable genes, which will be used for the downstream analysis. To speed up the analysis, we will just work with the top10 most variable genes:

# Data normalization
neuron <- NormalizeData(neuron, 
                        normalization.method = "LogNormalize", 
                        scale.factor = 10000)
## Normalizing layer: counts
#str(neuron)

# Identifying the most varialb genes
neuron <- FindVariableFeatures(neuron, 
                               selection.method = "vst", 
                               nfeatures = 2000)
## Finding variable features for layer counts
#str(neuron)

# Selecting the top 10 variable genes
top10 <- head(VariableFeatures(neuron), 10)
top10
##  [1] "Hbb-bs" "Hba-a1" "Hba-a2" "Cldn5"  "Igfbp7" "Rgs5"   "Nts"    "Snhg11"
##  [9] "C1qb"   "Hbb-bt"

Now lets visualize all the genes, indicating which are the most variable ones and labeling the 10 genes that we selected:

variableGenes <- VariableFeaturePlot(neuron)

Looking at the ElbowPlot, lets decide on how many PCs we will include to perform the clustering. Remember that using too many PCs, might find rare subtypes of cells but adds noise to the data; and using too few, we wont get enough information. This is a trial an error decision, so we never get it correct the first time!

  • Select a PC where the STDDEV plateaus (PLATEAU): _____

Once you have decided, use this value in the following code to perform the clustering and its visualization:

PLATEAU=15
# First we find the neighbors
neuron <- FindNeighbors(neuron, dims = 1:PLATEAU)
## Computing nearest neighbor graph
## Computing SNN
# str(neuron)

# Then we find the clusters (you can change the resolution, where lower values will give you more clusters)
neuron <- FindClusters(neuron, resolution = 0.2)

## 10:10:44 Optimization finished
neuron <- RunTSNE(neuron, dims = 1:PLATEAU)
#str(neuron)

# And finally we visualize the clusters
pca <- DimPlot(neuron, reduction = "pca")
umap <- DimPlot(neuron, reduction = "umap")
tsne <- DimPlot(neuron, reduction = "tsne")
CombinePlots(plots = list(pca,umap,tsne))
## Warning in CombinePlots(plots = list(pca, umap, tsne)): CombinePlots is being
## deprecated. Plots should now be combined using the patchwork system.

Q6. What is your favorite visualization?

Differential expression

In this part of the analysis, we will find genes that helps us to differentiate between the clusters, we call them marker genes. You can either compare one cluster to another or one cluster against all other clusters. Here lets focus on one vs all. Since the following command takes more than 20 mins to complete, download the resulting object from here and load it with the following code:

Lets select the first 5 markers for each cluster and visualize them. Replace REDUCTION with "pca", "tsne" or "umap", depending on which visualization you want to display:

# Identifying markers
top5 <- neuron.markers %>% group_by(cluster) %>% top_n(n = 5, wt = avg_logFC)
head(top5)
datatable(top5)

# Visualization
DoHeatmap(neuron, top5$gene)

DotPlot(neuron, features = top5$gene[seq(1,60,by=5)])

FeaturePlot(neuron, features = top5$gene[seq(1,60,by=5)], reduction = REDUCTION)
